<HEADLINE>
<P>
1ST MAN SENTENCED FOR DRAFT LIE IN AID BID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Vermont wildlife researcher has become the first person prosecuted for lying 
on a student aid form by saying that he had registered for the draft. He was 
sentenced to 18 months of probation, ordered to repay a Pell grant of $5,088 
and register for the draft as part of a plea bargain, federal officials said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Carl Veilleux, now 25, pleaded guilty on June 19 in Burlington, Vt., to a 
single count of entering false statements on a student assistance application 
in 1985, a misdemeanor, a spokesman for Vermont U.S. Atty. George Terwilliger 
III said. 
</P>
<P>
Men required to register for the draft who fail to do so are ineligible for 
federal student aid programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
