<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: MEDICAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Leslie Berkman, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Luther Medical Products Inc., a Tustin-based catheter manufacturer, said it has 
received $500,000 from a Japanese firm for the rights to market Luther's newest 
catheter in Japan, Korea, Taiwan, the Philippines and Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
Tate Scott, Luther's executive vice president, said the Japanese firm does not 
want to be identified until it begins its overseas marketing campaign sometime 
within the next 12 months. Scott would say only that the firm is a major 
distributor of catheters in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
Scott said the catheter covered by the new licensing will be sold under the 
trade name ACTIV. He said the catheter is exceptionally thin and thus easier to 
insert in veins for intravenous feedings and medications. Once in the vein, the 
catheter expands to allow greater flow of medication and softens to increase 
patient comfort. 
</P>
<P>
Scott said Luther's agreement with the Japanese marketing firm extends over 10 
years. 
</P>
<P>
Discussions are under way with other companies to distribute ACTIV catheters in 
the United States and worldwide, Scott said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
